bug.short_desc: StackOverflow after update from Kepler to Luna

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 244578 An internal error occurred during: "Building workspace".
I get this exception after the upgrade from Kepler to Luna when building my projects (maven, java, wtp)
Stacktrace attached.

Thanks for the report. From the stack trace it looks like your program has some recursive parameterized type with a wildcard. With this hint, could you possibly extract a small reproducing example?
I know that narrowing down a stack overflow is painful, but an example would be very helpful indeed.

I have the same issue, eclipse becomes unusable always throwing stack overflows and asking for restarts.
The project I'm working on is a large code base with ~60 OSGi bundles. Any suggestions on how I could narrow down the potential problematic code?

Created attachment 244667 example code
I think I've managed to isolate the class causing the problem. Could someone take a look at the attached test project and see if they get an exception?
On my machine, I get an exception every single time eclipse tries to do something with the PermissionDrivenPresenter class. It also seems to match the previous description of "class with recursive parameterized type with a wildcard".
Hope this helps.

With your test project i get the stack overflow too. But a different beginning than mine. Stephan, assigning to you since you seem to have done analysis. If you don't expect to find time, please feel free to assign to Sasi.

Prior art in this field: Method CaptureBinding.initializeBounds() has several pieces with comments like:
// prevent cyclic capture: given X<T>, capture(X<? extends T> could yield a circular type
To no avail for the case at hand.
The most recent change here was on behalf of bug 434044 comment 17. Indeed reverting that patch avoids the StackOverflow.
Since the same bug 434044 had a better fix after re-open, reverting the first attempt might actually be a good option. I'll test that approach ...

During previous analysis (bug 434044 comment 25) I had the impression that our implementation is not in line with the spec, because the spec says: "Capture conversion is not applied recursively." whereas we are fighting issues of recursive capture indeed (incl. StackOverflow like this bug and as early as bug 100128).
Today I found Philipe's bug 111208 comment 3, where he raises similar concerns, but then adds: "This would likely mean recursively on nested type arguments; but still should perform on wildcard bound (if any)."
And indeed, the spec seems to contain an intrinsic recursion, where it says (5.1.10):
"Si is a fresh type variable whose upper bound is Ui[A1:=S1,...,An:=Sn]"
This implies that each Si may depend on each Sj for arbitrary i,j. IOW, we first have to compute all Si before we can start computing any Si.
In that light I'm no longer surprised about the troubles we are facing.
In times of leisure (?) we might want to check if a genuine fix point computation can achieve the desired result in a more rigorous way. I'm thinking of avoiding all capture() calls inside CB.initializeBounds() and letting substitution take care of this, by looping over this substitution until a fix point is reached.

Released for 4.5 M1 via http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/?id=7de12fcc4142eb90ed2bed2f3f3346145c2a87fc

The fix is indeed (see comment 10) a simple revert of the first attempt from bug 434044 (which later had a better fix - reviewed by just about everybody in the team :) ). Given that the original problem from the other bug no longer needs that first attempt fix, the revert should be completely safe.
Fix has been verified by the reporter of duplicate bug 439611.

I too was unable to reproduce the issue using the nightly build (N20140724-2000).
